WEEK-10- Elastic Beanstalk

Prerequisites 
• 	A web application ready (e.g., ROOT.war, .zip, or code)----YOU CAN YOURS MAVEN PROJECT HERE 
 
Step 1: Open Elastic Beanstalk 
1.	Login to AWS Console 
2.	Under Compute section ->Search for Elastic Beanstalk 
3.	Click Create Application 
  
 Step 2: Create Application 
1.	Enter Application Name (e.g., MyApp) 
2.	Add description (optional) 
3.	Click Create 
  
 Step 3: Create Environment 
1.	Click Create Environment 
2.	Choose: 
	o 	 Web Server Environment (for web apps) 
3.	Click Select 
  
 Step 4: Configure Environment 
1.	Enter Environment Name  
2.	Choose Platform: 
o	Tomcat (for .war) 
As my web application is developed using Java 8 (as specified in  my pom.xml), I selected the platform as Java – Corretto 8 running on 64-bit Amazon Linux 2. 
o	Node.js / Python / PHP / etc. 
3.	Under Application Code: 
o	Select Upload your code  
1.	Service Role → Select existing  -LabRole 
2.	EC2 Key Pair → Optional (for SSH) 
3.	EC2 Instance Profile → select (e.g., LabInstanceProfile) 
 
 Step 6: Configure Network 
1.	Select VPC (default is fine) 
2.	Select Subnets 
3.	Enable Public IP 
  
 Step 7: Instance & Scaling Setup 
1.	Choose Instance type (e.g., t2.micro – free tier) 
Change environment type to Load Balanced 
2.	Set: 
o 	Min instances: 1 o 	Max instances: 2 (or more) 
3.	Load Balancer → Enabled (optional but recommended) 
Leave everything as default and click on skip to review 
  
 Step 8: Review & Create 
1.	Click Review 
2.	Click Create   
   
 Deployment Process 
•	AWS automatically creates: 
o	EC2 instances 
o	Load Balancer 
o	Auto Scaling Group 
After deployment: 
o	You will get a URL (domain link) 
o	Open it in browser → Your app will run  	    
 
Terminate all 
Environments-> Actions-> Terminate Environment 
 
